<paragraph id="8BF3DA14EF4E685ECEA8F87EFAA79A79" blockId="7.[151,1436,1909,2008]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,151,321]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="589" pageId="7" pageNumber="588">
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C4CA197EF4E6851CF28F87EFE6C9C8B" authorityName="Walsingham" authorityYear="1891" box="[327,445,1945,1971]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9380606EF4E6851CF28F87EFE6C9C8B" box="[327,445,1945,1971]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="588">Ptilothyris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also an Afrotropical genus, comprising about 20 species in the region (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDDA7E5EF4E6851CB78F87EFE929CEF" author="De Prins, J. &amp; De Prins, W." pageId="7" pageNumber="588" refId="ref5415" refString="De Prins, J. &amp; De Prins, W. (2020) Afromoths, online database of Afrotropical moth species (Lepidoptera). World Wide Web electronic publication. Available from: http: // www. afromoths. net (accessed 29 December 2020)" type="url" year="2020">De Prins &amp; De Prins 2020</bibRefCitation>
). The genus is superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C4CA197EF4E6851CD68F85AFC2D9CEF" authority="Park, 2018" authorityName="Park" authorityYear="2018" box="[775,1020,1981,2007]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Thubdora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="588" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9380606EF4E6851CD68F85AFCA49CEF" box="[775,885,1981,2007]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="588">Thubdora</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFDDA7E5EF4E6851CDEFF85AFC2D9CEF" author="Park, K. - T." box="[896,1020,1981,2007]" pageId="7" pageNumber="588" pagination="1085 - 1093" refId="ref5632" refString="Park, K. - T. (2018) A new genus Thubdora Park, gen. nov. and seven new species of the subfamily Torodorinae (Lepidoptera, Lecithoceridae) from Cameroon and Rep. of Congo, Africa. Journal of Asia-Pacific Entomology, 21, 1085 - 1093. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. aspen. 2018.07.018" type="journal article" year="2018">
Park, 
<quantity id="4CB477F1EF4E6851CDABF85AFC2D9CEF" box="[964,1020,1981,2007]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.125719999999999" pageId="7" pageNumber="588" unit="in" value="2018.0">2018</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in the wing venation, but it can be distinguished by the forewing more elongated and the antenna strongly bipectinate, usually dark brown, more or less flattened in basal half or longer, then creamy white beyond. The male genitalia can also be distinguished from those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4CA197EF41685ECED8FF38FEF49BC1" authorityName="Park" authorityYear="2018" box="[183,293,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Thubdora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="589" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9380606EF41685ECED8FF38FEF49BC1" box="[183,293,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="589">Thubdora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the uncus broadly developed, as wide as the basal plate of gnathos, fan-shaped; the gnathos with broad basal plate, usually trifurcate caudally with semi-ovate median lobe and similar sized lateral lobes; the juxta forming double plates, long ventral plate and dorsal plate; and the female genitalia with a hood-shaped signum.
</paragraph>
